{"id": "duc04-testb-2:2#7", "contents": "Hodler, the second most senior member of the IOC, alleged that 5 to 7 percent of the IOC membership asked for compensation for their vote. He called for a new electoral process, where the executive board or a select IOC group would decide which cities become Olympic hosts instead of the full IOC membership. Samaranch agreed that the current system was complicated, slow, and expensive, and that the time had come to explore change. The issue of vote-buying came to the fore due to the recent disclosure of scholarship payments made to six relatives of IOC members by Salt Lake City officials during their successful bid to host the 2002 Winter Games."}
